[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Stackhouse's oncology history is as follows:
1.  December 2002 - Surgical resection for a T3, N1, sigmoid adenocarcinoma.  Specific details regarding lymph node involvement unclear.
2.  January 2002 - Imaging showed two liver lesions.
3.  January 2002- Surgical resection by Dr. Jesse Wiseman of two hepatic lesions 2.5 x 2.3 x 2.0-cm and 1.2 x 1.0 x 0.9-cm, consistent with metastatic adenocarcinoma with a colon primary.
4.  2006 - Radiofrequency ablation of one lesion seen on a PET scan in the right lobe of the liver.
6.  January 13, 2010 - Colonoscopy showed a mass in the cecum.  Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma. No evidence of metastasis.
8.  January 29, 2010 - Right hemicolectomy by Dr. Thomas.  The surgical pathology report describes a grade 3  adenocarcinoma forming a 5.6- x 3.4- x 0.3-cm mass in the cecum invading into the pericolonic fat.  Two of 17 regional lymph nodes were positive for adenocarcinoma.  Staged at T3, N1, M0.
Mrs. Stackhouse is now coming to Belle Amis Memorial Hospital for a follow-up visit after her surgery and to discuss adjuvant chemotherapy.  She states that her postoperative course was very unremarkable and that she almost feels back to normal.  Her appetite is good.  She has not lost any weight.  Has no pain or other complaints.  She denies nausea and vomiting and palpitations.
A CT-scan done earlier today shows no evidence of recurrent disease or other abnormalities other than surgical sequelae.  A CEA is 2.1.  CBC is positive for a hemoglobin of 10.4.  Otherwise, CBC and chemistry are within normal and acceptable limits.

